# Django Rules

## Project Structure

- Follow Django's app-based structure; each app should have a single, well-defined responsibility.
- Keep apps small and reusable — if an app grows beyond ~10 models, consider splitting it.
- Place project-wide settings in a `settings/` package with `base.py`, `development.py`, and `production.py`.

```
project/
  config/
    settings/
      base.py
      development.py
      production.py
    urls.py
    wsgi.py
    asgi.py
  apps/
    users/
    orders/
  manage.py
```

## Models

- Always define `__str__` on every model for readable admin and shell output.
- Use `verbose_name` and `verbose_name_plural` in `Meta` for human-friendly labels.
- Add `db_index=True` or explicit `Index` objects in `Meta.indexes` for fields used in `filter()`, `order_by()`, or `JOIN` conditions.
- Use `get_or_create`, `update_or_create`, and `bulk_create`/`bulk_update` to reduce round-trips.
- Never use mutable default arguments in model fields — use `default=list` not `default=[]`.
- Prefer `ForeignKey(..., on_delete=models.PROTECT)` for critical relationships; be explicit about `on_delete` always.
- Use `select_related` for `ForeignKey`/`OneToOne` and `prefetch_related` for `ManyToMany`/reverse FK to avoid N+1 queries.

## Views

- Prefer **class-based views** (CBVs) for standard CRUD; use **function-based views** (FBVs) for simple or highly custom logic.
- Keep views thin — move business logic into service functions or model methods.
- Use `LoginRequiredMixin` / `@login_required` to protect authenticated views.
- Always return meaningful HTTP status codes.

## URLs

- Name every URL pattern and reference them with `reverse()` or `{% url %}` — never hardcode paths.
- Organise URLs using `include()` per app; keep the root `urls.py` clean.

## Forms & Validation

- Use Django `Form` or `ModelForm` for all user input — never parse `request.POST` manually.
- Add custom validation in `clean_<field>` or `clean` methods; raise `ValidationError` with descriptive messages.

## Templates

- Use template inheritance (`{% extends %}`, `{% block %}`) to avoid duplication.
- Never put business logic in templates — pass pre-computed data from views.
- Use `{{ variable|escape }}` (auto-escaped by default) to prevent XSS; mark safe strings explicitly with `mark_safe` only when absolutely necessary.

## ORM & Queries

- Use `QuerySet` chaining for all database reads; evaluate (hit the DB) as late as possible.
- Use `values()` or `values_list()` when you need only specific fields.
- Wrap multiple related writes in `transaction.atomic()`.
- Use `explain()` during development to inspect slow queries.

## Security

- Set `DEBUG = False` in production; never expose the secret key.
- Use Django's built-in CSRF protection — do not disable `CsrfViewMiddleware`.
- Configure `ALLOWED_HOSTS`, `SECURE_SSL_REDIRECT`, `SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE`, and `CSRF_COOKIE_SECURE` in production.
- Hash passwords with Argon2 (`django.contrib.auth.hashers.Argon2PasswordHasher`) for stronger security.

## Migrations

- Generate migrations with `makemigrations` and commit them to version control.
- Never edit migration files manually unless absolutely necessary; squash migrations periodically.
- Run `migrate` as part of the deployment pipeline.

## Admin

- Register models with `@admin.register(MyModel)`.
- Use `list_display`, `list_filter`, `search_fields`, and `readonly_fields` to improve usability.
- Restrict admin access to staff/superusers only.

## Testing

- Use `django.test.TestCase` for tests that need the database.
- Use `pytest-django` with `@pytest.mark.django_db` for pytest-style tests.
- Use `APIClient` or `RequestFactory` for view tests; prefer the former for integration tests.
- Use `factory_boy` or `mixer` for test data; avoid hardcoded fixtures.
- Keep test modules mirroring the app structure: `tests/test_models.py`, `tests/test_views.py`, etc.
